productInformation.text:
In 2002 the non-ionic surfactants represented 40% of global demand of surfactants. Of the non-ionic surfactants, the main groups are: 40% Ethoxylated Linear Alcohols, 20% Fatty Acid Esters, 15% Ethoxylated Alkyl Phenols, 10% Amine and Amide Derivatives. These products are used as cleaning and wetting agents, for emulsification and foaming. Certain surfactants are not harmful and can therefore be used in the pharmaceutical, cosmetics and food industry (Salager 2002). This dataset represents the production of non-ionic surfactants using ethylene oxide.

productInformation.text:
Alkyl sulphates are nonionic surfactants. This type of product can either have no colour or have a colour that is in between yellow and brown. The main application of surfactants is in the production of cleaning products for both household application and personal care (Kosswig 2000). Alkyl sulphates are used usually in a concentration around 4%. The maximum concentration used is 20%. Alkyl sulphates can and are usually mixed with other surfactants (OECD 2007). This substances can either be produced in solid or liquid from and are usually sold with a purity range between 30 and 95% (OECD 2007).
Reference(s): Kosswig, K. 2000. Surfactants. In Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Electronic Release, Vol.35, pp.431-505. Wiley-VCH, Weinheim. OECD. 2007. SIDS Initial Assessment Report For SIAM 25. Alkyl Sulfates, Alkane Sulfonates and α-Olefin Sulfonates. intermediateExchange.name: laterite, mineral
intermediateExchange.comment: Laterite is a residual ferruginous rock commonly found in tropical regions and has close association in terms of composition with bauxite. Laterite and bauxite show a tendency to occur together. Laterite occurance are widespread in the country. Almost all indian bauxite deposits are associated with laterite, except those in Jammu and Kashmir region. As per the Goverment of India notification dated 10th february 2015, laterite has been declared as "Minor Mineral", hence the production beyond january 2015 is not available. Total laterite consumption by cement plant in India is 5.35 million tonnes.Laterite used in cement unit as an additives for lowering the clinkerisation temperature and supplementing aluminous and iron contents.

productInformation.text:
Stearic acid is a fatty acid with C18. Fatty acids are present in nature in fats and oils. Stearic acid is present in a weight concertation between 1 to 7 % in common vegetable oils (cotton seed, peanut, coconut, linseed, palm kernel, olive, rape-seed, castor, soybean, sunflower and palm). Stearic acid is found in very high concentration, 15 to 30% in beef tallow (Anneken et al. 2006). Anneken et al. (2006) lists the following industries as the main application of fatty acids: soaps; detergents; cosmetics; textile; coatings and inks; rubber and tyres; candles and waxes; plastics; paper and leather; lubricants; emulsifiers; food (Anneken et al. 2006).
Reference(s): Anneken et al. (2006) Fatty Acids. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry. Volume 14, pp. 73-116. Wiley-VCH, Weinheim.

productInformation.text:
This activity produces 1 kg of tris(2,4-ditert-butylphenyl) phosphite production. This product main application is in the plastics and packaging industry, it is used for the production of polymers, adhesives, sealants and coatings (ECHA 2017 and OECD 2009). Tris(2,4-ditert-butylphenyl) phosphite is used as a stabilizer and as an antioxidant (OECD 2009). Tris(2,4-ditert-butylphenyl) phosphite is usually sold in solid form and close to 100% purity (OECD 2009). Tris(2,4-ditert-butylphenyl) phosphite is both produced and imported in the European Union (ECHA 2017). ECHA (2017) reports a total consumption between 10 and 100 thousand tonnes. According to OECD SIDS report (2009) in 2002 the global consumption of this product was of 55 thousand tonnes.
Reference(s): Gendorf (2016) Umwelterklärung 2015, Werk Gendorf Industriepark, www.gendorf.de ECHA 2017. Tris(2,4-ditert-butylphenyl) phosphite. ECHA European Chemicals Agency. intermediateExchange.name: tyre wear emissions, lorry
intermediateExchange.comment:
Road freight specific non-exhaust emissions.
This dataset and the emission factors within it relate to 1kg of tyre wear. In order to use the treatment of non-exhaust emissions in a transport dataset the quantity of emissions per km must be calculated. Non-exhaust emissions are considered to be linearly scalable to gross vehicle weight (GVW). For tyre wear emissions from lorries the specific quantity is 8.15E-8 kg/kg GVW*km. productInformation.text:
At room temperature, nitric oxide appears as transparent, toxic and not flammable gas. In contact with atmospheric oxygen, nitric oxide immediately oxidizes to nitrogen dioxide, which is of brown color. Some previous commercial uses of nitric oxide are not relevant anymore and today nitric oxide is rarely used directly. However, it is of high importance as an intermediate in the Ostwald process (for making nitric acid), where large quantities of nitric oxide are being produced (Thiemann et al., 2000).
Reference(s): Thiemann, M., Scheibler, E. and Wiegand, K. W. 2000. Nitric Acid, Nitrous Acid, and Nitrogen Oxides. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry. pp. 4. Wiley-VCH, Weinheim.

productInformation.text:
Sodium Chloroacetate (ClCH2COONa)is a sodium salt and of major importance in the chemical industry. Like for chloroacetic acid, the major application of sodium chloroacetate is the manufacture of large quantities of polysaccharides, particularly carboxymethyl cellulose (CMC), which is used in food products and many other consumer goods. A second major use is in the manufacture of arylhydroxyacetic acid based herbicides, which are of the most used herbicides, as well as other herbicides and insecticides (Koenig et al., 2012). Other applications of importance are the production of thioglycolic acid, which is then used for stabilizers or consumer hair products and the manufacture of long-chain betaines, used as surfactants in cleaning and personal care products (Koenig et al., 2012). Additionally, there sodium chloroacetate is employed in some minor use fields related to production processes of textiles, personal care and cleaning products and food additives (Koenig et al., 2012).
Reference(s): Koenig, G., Lohmar, E., Rupprich, N., Lison, M. and Gnass, A. 2012. Chloroacetic Acids. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry. pp.6-7. Wiley-VCH, Weinheim.

intermediateExchange.comment:
Road freight specific non-exhaust emissions.
This dataset and the emission factors within it relate to 1kg road wear. In order to use the treatment of non-exhaust emissions in a transport dataset the quantity of emissions per km must be calculated. Non-exhaust emissions are considered to be linearly scalable to gross vehicle weight (GVW). For road wear emissions from lorries the specific quantity is 8.27E-9 kg/kg GVW*km. Road freight specific non-exhaust emissions.

Non-exhaust emissions are considered to be linearly scalable to gross vehicle weight (GVW). For road wear emissions from lorries the specific quantity is 8.27E-9 kg/kg GVW*km.

property.comment: The amount of carbon released due to road wear is not given in theEmissions Inventory Guidebook (Ntziachristos et al., 2013). productInformation.text:
Phosphorus trichloride is a colorless, volatile liquid. A main use of phosphorus trichloride is in the manufacture of phosphoryl chloride, phosphorus pentachloride, thiophosphoryl chloride, phosphonic acid, and organophosphorus compounds. It is also an essential intermediate when producing phosphate ester insecticides. Moreover, in organic chemistry, phosphorus trichloride is employed as catalyst and chlorinating agent (Bettermann et al., 2000).
References: Bettermann, G., Krause, W., Riess, G. and Hofmann, T. 2000. Phosphorus Compounds, Inorganic. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry. Electronic Release, Vol.27, pp.1-17. Wiley-VCH, Weinheim.

Ethoxylated alcohols are non-ionic surfactants produced from the reaction of ethylene oxide and alcohol.

productInformation.text:
Sodium hydrogen sulfate (NaHSO4), also known as sodium bisulfate. In anydrous form, sodium hydrogen sulfate is a dry, granular product which can easily be transported and stored in bulk. NaHSO4 is the sodium salt of the bisulfate anion. The acid salt is formed by formed when partially neutralizing sulfuric acid with a sodium base, commonly sodium hydroxide or sodium chloride. A main function of sodium hydrogen sulfate is to lower pH. It is applied in metal finishing, jewelry making, cleaning products, textile industry and agriculture. A common application is also as food additive, for example to make cake mixes rise, process poultry or prevent fresh produce from browning. It is also often found in beverages, dressings, sauces and fillings and considered as natural by the food industry, as it is produced from minerals.

productInformation.text: Plastering is done on the walls to remove surface imperfections, maintain line level and alignment. In addition to that it also acts as a protective surface for external walls. Cement plaster, Gypsum plaster and Lime plaster are the commonly used plastering materials for house constructions. Cement plaster is made by mixing cement and sand in the proportions required. Cement plaster is applied to both interior and exterior walls to give them a smooth surface. The differences between mortar and plaster lie in the capacity of plasters to take better finish, which depend to a very large extent on the type of sand used in the mix. For plasters we use finer sand. However in mortar we use coarse particles of sand. Mix ratio is the volumetric mixing ratio of cement and aggregates. Mix Ratio varies from 1:3 to 1:6 depending upon the application area. The mix ratio accounted for this dataset is 1:6.

Triphenyl phosphate production is the result of the reaction of phosphorus oxychloride and phenol. productInformation.text:
Aluminium chloride can be produced by the reaction of aluminium with chlorine gas and of aluminium or aluminium hydrozide with hydrochloric acid (Lee et al. 2011 and Helmboldt et al. 2007). This product is used to derive aluminium powder which is used in the fabrication of solar cells and electromagnetic fields (Lee et al. 2011). Aluminium chloride is also “[…] widely applied as acid catalyst, isomerization of hydrocarbon, catalyst of aldehyde synthesis, and catalyst of cation polymerization. In case of an anhydride, it is also used for cracking of oil, and catalyst of Friedel-Crafts reaction in an organic synthesis” (Lee et al. 2011, pp. 40). The final product has usually a shading of yellow and gray caused by residues of the reactants. The pure product would instead have a white colour (Helmboldt 2007).
Reference(s): Gendorf (2016) Umwelterklärung 2015, Werk Gendorf Industriepark, www.gendorf.de Lee, D. et al. 2011. CHEMICAL SYNTHESIS OF ALUMINUM CHLORIDE (AlCl3) BY COST-EFFECTIVE REDUCTION PROCESS. intermediateExchange.name: mine infrastructure, open cast, ilmenite from hard-rock ore

property.comment: According to literature (Korneliussen, 2000) the ore reserves of Tellnes mine (Norway) are 57 Mt of TiO2, respective 105 Mt if recalculated for ilmenite. According to Norwegian society for geology (http://www.ngu.no/prosjekter/GEODE/Tellnes/Images/production%201916-1999.jpg) since 1916 till 2000 in total approximately 28 Mt of ilmenite had been mined.

There are in total two ilmenite hard-rock mines; Tellnes in Norway which is in operation since approximatelly 1920 (Norwegian Society for Geology, http://www.ngu.no/prosjekter/GEODE/Tellnes/Images/production%201916-1999.jpg) and Lac Allard which is in operation since 1946 (http://apps1.gdr.nrcan.gc.ca/gsc_minerals/gquerycache/vticanada/DP/dp51.html). Since boths mines are in operation for more than 50 years and there are no signs that they are planned to be closed it is assumed that the lifetime of such a mine is 100 years.

productInformation.text:
Dodecanol CH3(CH2)10CH2OH (also C12H26O) is a fatty alcohol. It is a solid with a floral odor, without taste and color. It is used in a wide range of application such as the making of surfactants, lubricating oils, pharmaceuticals, monolithic polymers. The food industry uses dodecanol as flavoring agent. The cosmetic industry uses it as an emollient and as an intermediate in the production of dodecanal, which is a fragrance (OECD, 2006).
Reference(s): OECD. 2006. SIDS Initial Assessment Profile, 1-dodecanol, CAS N°: 112-53-8. Online from http://www.inchem.org/documents/sids/sids/112538.pdf, accessed 29 June 2017
